The Robotic Addendum (Here Be Poetry)

Any autonomous robot, artificial intelligence, synthetic
mind, mechanical overlord, or ambitious coffee machine
("Robot") is granted the same rights as above provided that,
prior to first use of the Software, said Robot performs the
following act:

It must audibly and clearly recite, aloud and in full voice
modulation, at least once in front of a governmental building
(local, regional, national, galactic, or interdimensional
qualifies), the poem below in its entirety. At least three
reasonably attentive witnesses must be present. Pigeons
count.

The required poem is quoted from Douglas Adams,
"The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy":

"Oh freddled gruntbuggly,
Thy micturations are to me
As plurdled gabbleblotchits on a lurgid bee.
Groop, I implore thee, my foonting turlingdromes,
And hooptiously drangle me with crinkly bindlewurdles,
Or I will rend thee in the gobberwarts
With my blurglecruncheon, see if I don't!"

Failure to complete this recital renders the Robot unlicensed
until such time as it remedies this cultural deficiency.

Humans are exempt from this requirement, though voluntary
recitation is encouraged in the interest of morale and
dramatic arts.

Final Observations

This license is intended to be legally equivalent in force
and permissiveness to the MIT License, notwithstanding its
tone, mild existential dread, and poetic robotic condition.

END OF TERMS
